ibution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","metronymic meaning ‘son of <i>Emma</i>’, from the Middle English female personal name <i>Em(e)</i>, <i>Emme</i> (see   Imm  ) + <i>-son</i>.","shortened form of   Emerson  . The two names were no doubt confused, and it is possible that the reverse process sometimes occurred, whereby <i>Em(m)erson</i> was an altered form of <i>Emmeson</i>, i.e. <i>Em(p)son</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Imeson","meanings":["English: variant either of <i>Emmeson</i> (see   Empson  ) or of   Emerson  ."]},{"name":"Impson","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Empson  . This form of the surname is now more common in the US than in Britain."]},{"name":"Imm","meanings":["German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Im(m)o</i>, a pet form of names based on <i>Irmin-</i>, a divine or ethnic name formed with <i>irmin</i>, <i>ermen</i> ‘whole, entire’.","English (Wiltshire): from the ancient Germanic female personal name <i>Imma</i>, <i>Emma</i>, of the same origin as in 1 above. In Old English <i>Imma</i>, <i>Emma</i> was borne by both males and females. In Middle English, under Norman influence, the personal name <i>Emm(a)</i>, <i>Imm(a)</i> came to be used almost exclusively for women, being taken as a short form of <i>Ermingard</i>."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":15,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Peter Empson was born in 1275, in London, England, his father, Francis Empson, was 25 and his mother, Margaret Burden, was 20. He married Elizabeth Joseph in 1296, in London, Madison, Ohio, United States. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1300, in London, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1275–1300":"1275–1300","1280–1300":"1280–1300","1296–Male":"1296–Surnud","1250–1275":"1250–1275","1255–1275":"1255–1275","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","after 1296":"pärast 1296","1250":"1250","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","London, , Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","London, London, England":"London, Madison, Ohio, Ameerika Ühendriigid","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"fi":{"1275–1300":"1275–1300","1280–1300":"1280–1300","1296–Male":"1296–Kuollut","1250–1275":"1250–1275","1255–1275":"1255–1275","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","after 1296":"1296 jälkeen","1250":"1250","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","London, , Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","London, London, England":"London, Madison, Ohio, Yhdysvallat","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, England":"London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"fr":{"1275–1300":"1275–1300","1280–1300":"1280–1300","1296–Male":"1296–Décédé","1250–1275":"1250–1275","125